BOOK I.——TIIE LANDING IN AFRICA.

THE wrath of June, jealous for the glory of Carthage, compels the long wanderings of AEneas, and detains the Trojan exiles from destined Italy (vv. 1-33). She beholds them glad on their voyage, and solicits AEolus, god of winds, to overwhelm them with a tempest: the storm bursts forth (34-91). The Trojan fleet is scattered and in peril: but Neptune lifts his head and stills the waves (92—156). AEneaS, with seven ships, reaches the coast of Africa, where he finds food and rest (157-222).
